    The root cause of the crash is a double-free error, which occurs when       
    free(b->name) is called twice on the same memory block.                     
                                                                                
    Walkthrough of Program State:                                               
                                                                                
     1 main() calls load_blob("abcdef"):                                        
        • The name argument is "abcdef", which has length 6.                    
        • load_blob allocates a blob_t struct and calls strdup(name) to copy    
          the string into b->name.                                              
        • The condition if (strlen(name) > 4) is true (6 > 4), so the function  
          enters the recoverable error path.                                    
        • At line 23: free(b->name); is called → this frees the memory          
          originally allocated by strdup(name).                                 
        • Then, b->size = 0; and return b; → the partially allocated blob_t is  
          returned, but with b->name now pointing to freed memory.              
     2 Back in main():                                                          
        • b is now a valid pointer (not NULL), but b->size == 0, so the         
          condition if (b && b->size == 0) is true.                             
        • The program prints: "load_blob: empty blob, cleaning up\n".           
        • Then, destroy_blob(b) is called.                                      
     3 destroy_blob() executes:                                                 
        • if (!b) return; → skips.                                              
        • free(b->name); → this attempts to free the already-freed b->name      
          buffer → UB (undefined behavior), triggering the "Deallocation of     
          freed memory" error.                                                  
                                                                                
    Root Cause:                                                                 
                                                                                
     • The load_blob function freed b->name on the recoverable error path, but  
       did not nullify the pointer.                                             
     • The destroy_blob function later attempts to free the same pointer        
       again, resulting in a double free.                                       
     • Even though load_blob intends to hand back a partially initialized       
       object, it leaves b->name dangling, and destroy_blob assumes it is       
       valid to free.                                                           
                                                                                
    Why This Is Wrong:                                                          
                                                                                
     • After free(b->name); in load_blob, b->name is a dangling pointer.        
     • destroy_blob has no way to know that b->name is already freed — it just  
       calls free(b->name) unconditionally.                                     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Minimal Fix:                                                                
                                                                                
    The minimal fix is to set b->name = NULL after freeing it in load_blob, so  
    that destroy_blob will skip the free if it's already null.                  
                                                                                
    Fix in load_blob (line 23):                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     free(b->name);                                                             
     b->name = NULL;  // Prevent double-free                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This ensures destroy_blob will not attempt to free a freed pointer.         
                                                                                
    Thorough Root-Cause Fix:                                                    
                                                                                
    Even better, the destroy_blob function should only free b->name if it is    
    non-null, but the real issue is design: freeing one part of a struct and    
    expecting another function to clean up the rest without nulling pointers.   
                                                                                
    But a safer and more robust design is to not rely on the caller to free     
    b->name if it is already freed elsewhere.                                   
                                                                                
    So the ideal fix is to make destroy_blob defensive:                         
                                                                                
    Improved destroy_blob:                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_blob(blob_t *b) {                                      
         if (!b) return;                                                        
         if (b->name) {                                                         
             free(b->name);                                                     
             b->name = NULL;  // Prevent future use                             
         }                                                                      
         free(b);                                                               
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    But since the load_blob function already frees b->name, the minimal fix in  
    load_blob is sufficient and preferred, because:                             
                                                                                
     • destroy_blob should not depend on external knowledge of internal state.  
     • The responsibility lies with load_blob to ensure ownership is            
       transferred cleanly.                                                     
                                                                                
    --------------------------------------------------------------------------  
                                                                                
    Final Recommendation:                                                       
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
     1 Fix in load_blob at line 23:                                             
                                                                                
        free(b->name);                                                          
        b->name = NULL;  // Prevent double-free in destroy_blob                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This prevents the double-free by nulling the pointer after freeing, so      
    destroy_blob will avoid freeing already-freed memory. This is both minimal  
    and effective.                                                              
                                                                                
